Lemma 3 shows that once the firm chooses defensive spending optimally within a given regime, its remaining decision is how broadly to deploy AI (). In each regime, the firm therefore chooses by weighing the marginal productivity gain from broader deployment against the marginal security burden implied by that regime. In the corner regime, where AI-specific defense is not yet worthwhile, deployment rises with complementary organizational readiness and rises with capability only when the loss environment is sufficiently mild. In the interior regime, the firm continues to broaden deployment only if the added productivity from greater capability exceeds the combined burden of residual breach damage and defensive expenditure. The two regime-specific expressions connect smoothly at the boundary because the firm changes its response rule once defense becomes worthwhile, not because deployment jumps discontinuously.
4.4 Main Results
Proposition 2 (Security Discount).
Let . The security discount is
is continuously differentiable at , increasing in and , and independent of .
Proof.
From the firm’s perspective, the security discount is the wedge between what it would deploy if cyber risk were irrelevant and what it can justify once the governance-capability gap is taken into account. As capability advances, the firm’s no-risk deployment benchmark rises, but so does the amount of deployment withheld because the security burden also grows. The discount is therefore not a fixed cost of adopting AI. It is an endogenous gap between the firm’s no-risk deployment benchmark and its economically sustainable deployment under the current loss environment. Figure A2 in Appendix R visualizes this security discount, and Table A1 summarizes the interior comparative statics for deployment, defense, breach probability, and firm value.
Remark 1.
The security discount widens as capability advances. Stronger AI therefore raises the firm’s no-risk deployment benchmark and, at the same time, increases the amount of deployment withheld under the gap. Investments that reduce become more valuable as capability advances because they narrow this wedge.
Proposition 3 (Deployment Paradox).
Suppose . Under capability–damage bundling,
If : (i) optimal deployment is strictly decreasing in capability for all ; (ii) strictly increasing for ; (iii) the global minimum is attained at . If : for all , and no paradox arises.
Proof.
This sign reversal is not an artifact of the square-root form in the baseline interior solution. Appendix O and Appendix Q show that related sign-reversal regions can arise under generalized damage and productivity functions whenever the exposure-linked security burden grows sufficiently strongly relative to the marginal productivity gain.
Remark 2.
The deployment paradox is a rational organizational response to the gap, not an irrationality or misperception. In the corner regime, each capability increment adds to deployment when . In the interior regime, gross productivity grows linearly with while the expected security burden scales with ; the turning point at marks where the linear productivity channel begins to dominate. The paradox resolves either when capability crosses , or when -reducing governance investment lowers below 1 (Proposition 4). The boundary marks where defensive investment becomes worthwhile, not where the paradox emerges or resolves.
The mechanism also has a straightforward cross-industry interpretation. Firms facing the same capability improvement can respond differently depending on their loss environment. In a high-loss environment, a more capable system is deployed with broader authority exposure under the gap, so the damage amplification from capability growth can outpace the productivity gain over an intermediate range. The firm then responds by reducing its deployment footprint. In a milder loss environment, by contrast, the same capability improvement raises deployment because the productivity channel continues to dominate. The paradox is therefore not that the AI system is undesirable in absolute terms; it is that the firm’s current controls may be unable to safely contain what the more capable system can reach.
Proposition 4 (Effect of Governance Maturity on Deployment).
A reduction in , reflecting governance investment that closes the gap, increases optimal deployment:
Both are strictly negative; both yield at .
Proof.
This comparative static has a direct managerial interpretation. A reduction in does not simply lower expected breach losses holding deployment fixed. It also relaxes the security burden that constrains how broadly the firm can use capable AI in the first place. Governance investments that improve containment, segmentation, and privilege design can therefore operate as enabling investments rather than as separate compliance costs. By reducing the loss environment the firm faces, they convert more of AI’s technical capability into economically viable deployment. Figure A1 in Appendix R illustrates this comparative static by plotting optimal deployment as the loss environment changes.
Remark 3.
Reducing below 1 eliminates the paradox region entirely: for all once . Closing the gap therefore does more than increase deployment at the margin. It restores the standard monotone relationship between capability and deployment by moving the firm out of the paradox regime altogether.
4.5 Attack-Surface Channel Under Severe Governance Failure
The baseline specification is intentionally conservative. In this case, the attack-surface channel cancels in equilibrium because the firm can offset a broader attack surface by scaling defense proportionally with deployment. The paradox therefore operates through the damage channel: more capable AI raises conditional breach severity under the gap. This subsection relaxes that proportional-offset property. Formally, consider with . Under this specification, increases in , so optimal defense can no longer fully offset superlinear attack-surface growth. The attack-surface channel then begins to reinforce the baseline damage-channel mechanism. A local sign-reversal condition via the implicit function theorem is:
This is a local result under interior feasibility, not a global theorem. Appendix P provides the full derivation via the implicit function theorem.
Asymmetric attacker advantage.
The specification also has a natural interpretation in terms of attacker–defender asymmetry. In practice, adversaries can probe many entry points simultaneously while the defender must allocate resources across all of them; a single successful intrusion suffices for the attacker, while the defender must protect every node. This structural asymmetry means that the effective attack-surface elasticity the defender faces may exceed one—each additional AI-enabled entry point is harder to defend proportionally than the last, because the attacker can concentrate effort while the defender cannot. Under , this asymmetry is partially captured: the condition becomes easier to satisfy as grows, reflecting the compounding difficulty of defending an expanding surface against a concentrated adversary.
The baseline should therefore be read as a conservative benchmark for isolating the damage-channel mechanism; can additionally strengthen sign reversal locally under interior feasibility.
4.6 Endogenous Capability Choice: When Firms Rationally Reject Frontier AI
The main model treats as exogenous. However, the gap also shapes capability selection: under gap conditions, deploying a more capable system widens the damage channel, while retaining a legacy system limits exposure. The same high-gap environments that generate the deployment paradox can also distort capability choice itself. A firm may rationally reject a frontier upgrade, and that rejection can persist even after the local paradox in deployment has ended because firm value has not yet recovered.
