Appendix R Comparative Statics
Appendix S Extensions
S.1 Governance Adjustment and the Paradox Region
When capability improvements are not matched by governance investment, the paradox region persists over a wider range of conditions. By contrast, when governance investment reduces , the paradox region narrows and the negative capability–deployment relationship weakens. Industries that improve governance maturity alongside capability adoption should therefore experience an earlier exit from the paradox region.
Remark 5 (Governance Adjustment and Boundary Conditions).
Consider an extension in which capability improvement is accompanied by governance investment that reduces . The paradox region is defined by . Any force that raises or lowers moves the firm toward the standard monotone relationship. Three cases apply: (1) Governance-led adjustment: paradox region shrinks because governance investment lowers . (2) Capability-led adjustment: paradox region shrinks because capability rises beyond the threshold. (3) Limited governance adjustment: if remains high, the paradox region remains broader. A richer dynamic optimization is beyond the scope of the current paper.
S.2 Endogenous Governance and Rational Security Debt
A natural critique of the baseline model is that firms suffering from the deployment paradox should immediately invest to eliminate the governance gap. We show here that when governance restructuring entails convex organizational costs, a residual gap may optimally persist.
Suppose the firm inherits and can invest to achieve , at convex cost , where captures institutional friction. The firm maximizes , where denotes the maximized baseline profit. At an interior optimum, the FOC is . By the envelope theorem applied to the interior-regime profit , the marginal value of reducing is:
Substituting the optimal defense gives , which simplifies (15) to:
This holds in the interior regime (); in the corner regime (), and an analogous calculation yields , confirming the marginal benefit of reducing is strictly positive across both regimes.
Whenever the solution is interior, the optimal governance investment satisfies:
Remark 6 (Rational Accumulation of Security Debt).
As , and . By continuity, if the inherited environment initially lies in the paradox region—that is, if —there exists a threshold such that for all : the firm remains in the paradox region despite having a positive incentive to reduce . The persistence of the governance-capability gap is therefore a structural consequence of convex organizational friction, not managerial myopia. From (17), external interventions that reduce adjustment frictions or require minimum governance investment—such as governance subsidies or segmentation standards—can raise effective governance investment and endogenously contract the paradox region, consistent with the -reducing policy channel discussed in Section 7.
S.3 Strategic Attacker
If attacker capability scales with , breach risk becomes more sensitive to AI deployment and capability, further tightening the paradox region. The baseline likely understates the paradox in such environments, but a game-theoretic treatment is left for future work.
S.4 Heterogeneous AI Applications
With high-authority () and low-authority () AI, high-gap firms would shift portfolios toward lower-authority applications as increases within the paradox region—substituting toward AI uses outside the gap even as aggregate deployment declines.

